{"questionId":"35035025","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>To verify whether this relationship applies in a different direction from the city centre, Xavie considers two locations, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>, both an equal distance from the city centre. They take a random sample of seven apartments from each location and record the prices (in millions of dollars) in the following tables.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/1c492d9d0cf63030ee904c96e7d361339d41ea0e.png\" width=\"448\" height=\"164\"></p>\n<p>Xavie conducts a <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>-test, at the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mo>%</mo></math> level of significance, to see if the mean apartment price in location <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is different to the mean apartment price in location <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>. They assume the population variances are the same.</p>\n<p>For this test, Xavie takes the null hypothesis to be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>μ</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>μ</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find this estimated price.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempt to substitute&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>19</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></math>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0992075</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>×</mo><mn>19</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>19150</mn><mo>…</mo></math></strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>24704</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>price&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo> </mo><mi>million</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mi>AUD</mi></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>24704</mn><mo>…</mo><mo> </mo><mi>million</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"35035025","referenceCode":"24M.2.SL.TZ1.1di","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find this estimated price.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.4—Pearsons, scatter diagrams, eqn of y on x"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":3}
